02","1157":"1157","1300":"1300","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1272":"1272","Cilgedin, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanfair,Cilgedin,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Llanfair Grange, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burchill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Somerset): variant of   Burchell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burchell","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birchill in Derbyshire or Birchills in Staffordshire, both named in Old English with <i>birce</i> ‘birch’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir David Burchill of Llanfair Cilgedin was born in 1202, in Llanfair Grange, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, William Burchill, was 48 and his mother, Jane de Walbieffe, was 46. He had at least 2 daughters with de Turberville. He died in 1272, in Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 70, and was buried in Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1202–1272":"1202–1272","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1225–1300":"1225–1300","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1157–Female":"1157–Surnud","1205":"1205","Abt 1272":"umbes 1272","1225":"1225","1202":"1202","1157":"1157","1300":"1300","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1272":"1272","Cilgedin, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanfair,Cilgedin,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Llanfair Grange, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1202–1272":"1202–1272","1177–Male